document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended with Learning Progressions Science

B412EBF89F5F408089590E9D4695F7AD.description:
Compare the cell to a factory and show how cells make
products for an organism.

0FFB37CA31884915A92464DF7EFA4916.description:
Identify the products of photosynthesis. [Use pictures
to complete a diagram of the process of photosynthesis
(picture of sun, tree, water, oxygen, carbon dioxide and
glucose)]

F1976CE5674A421FB69F445F72601E0B.description: Identify the products of cellular respiration.

37A490F15BE74A079BBF02346609A3F8.description:
Investigate plant seedlings in different environments
(temperature, pH) to show optimum range of growth.

21143E05C2CF45B89467A7C8B7BE8AD2.description:
Identify
photosynthesis and
cellular respiration
as occurring in a
cell.

9B6B749A463A4795BA07AE9A781B91EA.description:
Complete a
diagram that depicts
the process of
photosynthesis.

6FC2EB544B0D4F45B54D268E42668755.description:
Describe
how the cell needs
specific conditions
(e.g., temperature,
pH) in order
to perform its
essential functions
(e.g., respiration,
photosynthesis).

620E4606F87F4C058AE333A912F89670.description:
Cellular Processes
• Characteristics of life
regulated by cellular
processes
• Photosynthesis,
chemosynthesis, cellular
respiration, biosynthesis of
macromolecules

2D22FE61376D4C5E946E47A1BAF6544F.description: Recognize that all living things are made of cells.

2CC0F63D620B46B8BE9FF572FD5C85C7.description: Recognize that organelles do specific jobs for the cell.

B0660AA8AF99407B9413D371E06A17DE.description: Recognize that cells are classified by their cell parts.

64032590D81144C38DA3DD9AC071CC18.description:
Given a cell with missing part, identify what function the
cell is unable to do and how that affects the cell.

6F94F83AC7F74424BD41BCFE10418713.description: Show what cell type is responsible for photosynthesis.

1E0CEF0EFFB3432C9702D5C0100C8D02.description:
Given a variety of cells sort into prokaryotic and eukaryotic
cells.

E0E0A3EAF8D44CB2949996C1F12825EF.description: Identify a cell as prokaryotic or eukaryotic.

FD0684F0A007417EA0BA47AD4183EBA0.description:
Recognize that materials need to enter and leave the cell
through the cell membrane.

0EF3484486364AFAAF013CCC94421B6D.description: Model materials going into and out of the cell.

39EF0E21DCE84775B96025F6CA287756.description:
Identify the
function of the cell
membrane.

17324D6609AD4C51A0191A673E23D7AE.description:
Match
the organelle with
the process it
helps to execute
(e.g., chloroplast,
photosynthesis).

6CE253E99D124BB3A6B77883FF37CCEA.description:
Compare
and contrast a
prokaryotic cell
and a eukaryotic
cell.

CDDC4123FB3C46A197EEA193830F0518.description:
Cell Structure
• Structure, function and
interrelatedness of cell
organelles
• Eukaryotic cells and
prokaryotic cells

70532098F2B84258AD11DB9841CA4AD4.description:
Recognize that natural events will change an ecosystem
impacting organisms.

D742AF9807664043A7B397196B25A7EB.description:
Recognize the human activities can change an ecosystem
impacting organisms.

B316F1FA079B4E908DAADC763469F6FD.description:
Discuss what happens to organisms in an ecosystem
after a natural event. (Show pictures of natural events and
match them with the aftermath photos of the environment.)

356F242A5E384355A378F72CC2046E83.description:
Discuss what happens to organisms in an ecosystem after
a human activity. (Show pictures of human activities such
as strip mining, mall building, home developments and
match them with the aftermath photos of the environment.)

589D5314287B429397A62E9451D18047.description:
Use populations numbers of native species after the
introduction of zebra mussels to the Great Lakes to
provide an example of how human activities can impact an
ecosystem.

4C95EC1EDADB40A5BA34FD2F2E97029D.description:
Match worldwide temperature data to a given environment
and the changes that have occurred to the populations
that live there. (e.g., polar ice caps, coral reefs).

97FF1B696FBB4C10A8572A1C27EE09CC.description:
Identify
factors that can
harm organisms
in an environment
(e.g., drought,
floods, volcanic
eruption, habitat
loss, new species
etc.).

812A347557EF46489949806F70FB8BAA.description:
Match the
cause (e.g., drought,
flood, habitat loss,
new species) to its
effect on organisms in
an ecosystem.

E431CDBA66C548C38D2B960F7C7D8BDA.description:
Describe
how drought, flood,
volcanic eruption,
habitat loss, or
introduction of a
new species may
affect the diversity
in an ecosystem.

127E9A66DEEA4D1F96F1B50A7011B7F9.description:
Loss of Diversity
• Climate change
• Anthropocene effects
• Extinction
• Invasive species

B9780070FF074EF1BCC5CAE4BFE58579.description:
Examine a given ecosystem and identify the relationships
between organisms.

C11B9A00E4FB4A1A94C567DA9CAF55C3.description:
Match the cause to the effect of a change to an
ecosystem. (Given two pictures of an ecosystem and
an event which occurred identify which came first (e.g.,
meadow, forest, apartment complex, volcanic eruption).

A8B0C885DD274EA39FDF1718A3018D70.description:
Given an environment and an event (natural or man
made) predict what organisms will survive, thrive or perish
as a result of that event.

B6F340649E4345BE82EBE65E4931C4B1.description:
Given an ecosystem that has experienced an event
(natural or man made) discuss how an impacted organism
may change the dynamics of the ecosystem (carrying
capacity).

BC0BFECBE0BC4921BDDBD9AB1899393D.description:
When
given a set of
before and after
pictures of an
ecosystem,
(e.g., meadow
changed to farm,
forest changed
to apartment
buildings) observe
the human caused
changes.

38635C4A497A4327A8728BE45ABDF980.description:
Identify
how a human or
natural change to an
ecosystem results in a
change to a predator
or prey population.

0B8434FDF08E4C3AB42DF3D19AB32A3C.description:
Identify
how both
populations will
change in a
predator/prey
relationship, when
given a model of
an ecosystem that
is not in balance
(e.g., carrying
capacity).

6571F45D677C4A90B1CFDC178B429FF4.description:
Ecosystems
• Equilibrium and
disequilibrium
• Carrying capacity

39BE3AC963B74EE19489114E2FC4014B.description:
Given two animals or plants, identify which of them is most
likely to survive in a certain environment and match which
traits would help it survive.

D69410EBAB8741A0990A9CF936C75FCF.description:
Given pictures of two environments and a set of organism
picture cards, place the organisms in the environment
where they are most likely to survive.

588DC9A3D077447383E6DF6B46F2821C.description:
Predict what will happen to an ecosystem when a
population of organisms (wolves, ash trees) moves in or
out.

0F4A3EF828B54963A673CBB8908CF4D8.description:
Show data (graphs or charts) for population sizes of
predatory/prey for a particular environment and show how
one species impacts another (e.g., wolves and moose oin
Isle Royale).

762D14EB27D744C693BA8207BF7190A8.description:
When
given an
environment,
recognize a plant
or an animal that
could survive in
that environment.

761CBBC64F404991A1B3239171793994.description:
When given
two examples of an
animal or plant in a
given environment,
describe which one
would have the higher
chance to survive or
reproduce based on
traits (e.g., fur coat
thickness, coloration).

C90754D87EFF4F3AAE052023213995C1.description:
Explain
how low genetic
diversity impacts
population size,
energy flow or the
cycle of matter in a
given environment
(e.g., Isle Royale
Wolf population).

D4DCA85FDEC64A47B8B58039BBD4ED7F.description:
Use a cladogram with pictures of the organisms to
describe changes from one clade to the next (an organism
compared to its ancestors). Show the evolution of a trait.

97CA59996AA940DE83D7817CC495382B.description:
Use the horse as an example, show pictures of earlier
forms and discuss the changes that have occurred.

5924F9A86AFE4AF192DE473177675780.description:
Given a cladogram with pictures, make a prediction of
what the next generation willould look like based on a
given environment.

CF136FE382264C32A7AF89E6832E0109.description:
Given
a visual
representation,
identify a species
that has changed
over the course of
many generations
(e.g., cladogram
diagram).

F2A7EF0693054D6BA8C16B32EDFD751A.description:
Diagram
and describe the
evolutionary change
in a species.

22D1F650CC1145A98BF9AFA386B91F93.description:
Identify
evolutionary
changes to a
given species that
have allowed the
species to continue
to survive and
reproduce.

91B530906CC749648BEC677FC1880971.description:
Speciation
• Biological classification
expanded to molecular
evidence
• Variation of organisms
within a species due to
population genetics and
gene frequency

99EEA227B8464C96B2E743562142048A.description:
Given pictures of bird beaks or teeth of mammals and
discuss what kinds of food the animal would be best able
to eat.

49DB64FEFC2347CA81595450FC497751.description:
Discuss how coloration would impact a predator prey
relationship, if prey is easy to see it is easy to catch and
eat. (Pick up colored candies from a colored background
and discuss why some colors are easier to see.)

DEDE6480CF664C62A69C15844A130441.description:
Provide pictures of animals or plants with a variety of traits
and match them to the environment in which they would
survive (e.g., lots of fur in a snowy region).

8310CA4B817344D2BA0C3AFE41FBB110.description: Recognize that traits are produced by genes.

202D71508A37455EBB1A695263BB3E3D.description:
Discuss how successful genes in a population get passed
on through reproduction.

D26E36CB85024E9D86BB7BF85C64415E.description:
Discuss how an organism must survive in order to pass on
its traits (genes).

FBF87F734E4E4629B4D48DCF700D516E.description:
When given
a plant or animal,
identify traits that
help it to survive in
its environment.

EF5640E82EEC44DFACD4A7D1E172E8A4.description:
When given a
population of animals
or plants, identify
how variation in traits
impacts their ability to
survive and reproduce
(e.g., populations of
endangered species).

54526E99B3604BC4942A0F1778C347B8.description:
Describe
how the presence
or absence of traits
may help some
individuals in a
plant or animal
population survive
and reproduce in
their environment
(e.g., natural
selection).

4EF2CABA2B3747518E293E4790715810.description:
Mechanisms
• Natural selection
• Mutation
• Genetic drift
• Gene flow (immigration,
emigration)
• Sexual selection

F58A34888CF24B379F96BED7B2E3F702.description:
Taste examples of heirloom tomatoes and store bought
hybrids or field corn and hybrid sweet corn.

D9DFF65994134F8F9EA1374FE1A41C5D.description: List the differences in the tastes of heirloom produce.

AA29B856326E41298CA7782F0BCB6D76.description:
Describe why humans would want to change DNA in an
organism.

930C34939023406C89599971183FA744.description:
Discuss important attributes a farmer should consider for a
food crop (yield, taste, shelf life).

EB80DCA7639240718B7DE9E29572F879.description:
Show pictures of animals and plants that have been
genetically altered for food production.

67D9FF44352E47BAA123DFCCB677F558.description:
Identify one
reason DNA would be
purposely altered by
humans.

711450BBA43A45919FE31C5C68C2AF1C.description:
Describe
specific ways in
which scientists
have used DNA to
help people or the
environment (e.g.,
sweeter fruit, etc.).

ACB7A36EA68446A3BE0F73AC348BD1C3.description:
Observe a population of organisms to identify differences
in individuals.

4393BA0253DD484785004618D6B64D1A.description:
In a given population identify the various forms of a trait
that exist (e.g., fur color).

75E27693213248A6B0ACDB62CECEB129.description:
Recognize that changes in DNA which causes different
characteristics and functions are called mutations..

51A9D1B0529046D6A8E3F7810E12A5D5.description:
Recognize that only mutations in sex cells get passed on
to offspring.

DE439DC94B3842EF8AAD503B0BD19AB1.description:
Recognize that not all mutations have an impact on an
organism.

316EC02DECF44826A1BC863F941D3E3A.description:
Identify
traits that can
vary among a
population (e.g.,
eye color, beak
shape, etc.).

A1EE0286FF574C0893810798AD28F8CC.description:
Recognize
that genes can be
altered and that those
changed genes may
then be passed to
offspring.

E08F6AD482BB47A68F0D77CF8F13D0C5.description:
Describe
how some
mutations can be
helpful and some
can be harmful to
organisms.

BF2BF4059ED3432AAE956B8D4084F7FA.description:
Observe a family pedigree and note the similarities and
differences of the offspring.

E35C75EC64414F06B28EFC1B5DD0949D.description:
Recognize that sex cells contain half the genetic
information for the next generation.

C7B165A4792D4965871E1CAFBD5473B7.description:
Identify the genetic combination for female is XX and male
is XY.

BBA386BB811A490B831BE06A619BC3F6.description:
Identify the products of meiosis, sex cells (egg and
sperm).

98A0C1A29D9C430296A897C8D96C7DF4.description:
Identify fertilization as sex cells combining.to produce a
unique offspring.

A86DD5B0BE9A44EA8AF001CE86D2F462.description:
Identify
X and Y as
female and male
chromosomes.

25BD40E8C5524D4C9F23AD88257605F6.description:
Recognize
that genes combine
during sexual
reproduction which
causes the traits of
offspring to not be
exact replicas of
either parent.

FB504D7D707744E3A52C7DFC2BA23C9D.description:
Predict
the possible
phenotypes of an
offspring when
given the genotype
of the parents
(e.g., using a
Punnett square).

99F60C4240F54388AF9BD8AFDB20B734.description:
Recognize that the sequence of DNA is specific for
development of specific traits.

4200206A82B54AED9B4701C7BCCDA127.description:
Recognize that if the sequence of DNA is changed, the
trait changes.

E00492618008428285B59B37E8E09AFA.description:
Recognize that in sexual reproduction DNA is contributed
from two parents to produce a new organism (genetically
unique).

174CDBFE930D42E5A0B9FB229BFF1699.description:
Recognize that changing the sequence of DNA may alter
the development of a trait if the resulting protein is altered.

20829FDD91434C6E97B3435AA21D114D.description:
When
given a
representation of
individuals from
the same parents,
identify variations
in physical traits.

5672A7839BE240748649F0FD21ECFECC.description:
Recognize
that genes are
made up of DNA,
so changing the
segments of DNA can
alter genes.

76B2C19185B441A79FBC25644F2723FC.description:
Recognize
that changing the
segments of DNA
molecules can
alter genes.

82B9936F7D934C75A807785AA1C14668.description:
Structure and Function
of DNA in Cells

9D9370807525481C8F1B026B8212A206.description: Recognize that DNA is a set of instructions for the cell.

D849F67FC46249D794386F40726E85C6.description: Manipulate a physical model of DNA.

1DB2F971BCFD44039E2ADEFD2670E416.description:
Illustrate that portions of DNA represent a gene that codes
for a variety of traits (hair, skin, feathers, leaves).

D0C41919B1934F58B3555C314EBB6824.description:
Recognize that DNA codes for proteins that physically
make the traits.

240FD3701F1B4C0DAC510DDD50C8D7FC.description:
Recognize
that genes are
made up of DNA.

9395F88E0C32483EAD284FB795FC2AD4.description:
Communicate
that genes code for
specific traits (e.g.,
eye color, hair color).

573C353092964E7CBBB2A66CFA0039B0.description:
Describe
that different genes
code for proteins
that determine
different traits.
